<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-604-651 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 604 651.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 15 1991 v13 n15 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Redundancy of information foils pattern data compression. (TechTalk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Pattern-based data compression depends on the inherentlynon-random nature of most information.andP;  Non-random data can beanalyzed, encoded and compressed in size using a variety ofalgorithms.andP;  These schemes reduce file size by eliminatingexcessive redundancy, but a major problem is the fact thatredundancy is essential to minimize loss of information in theevent of errors.andP;  A single bit lost from a compressed file cancause a disastrous loss of information.andP;  Redundant files sometimesstore less than one logical bit worth of data per physical bit.andO;Compression strategies can yield files that store several logicalbits per physical bit.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data CompressionRedundancySoftware DesignPerformance ImprovementProgram Development TechniquesAlgorithms.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>